**Conclusion**  
The soft‑max model for alignment  

\[
P(A_i\!\mid\!\mathcal{C}_i,\mathcal{D}_i,\mathcal{M})
=\frac{\exp\!\bigl(\sum_{j\in\mathcal N(i)}\alpha_{ij}\kappa_{ij}
+\beta_{ij}\phi_{ij}
+\gamma_i\mathcal H(\mathcal M_i)\bigr)}
{\sum_{A\in\mathcal A}\exp\!\bigl(\sum_{j\in\mathcal N(i)}\alpha_{ij}\kappa_{ij}
+\beta_{ij}\phi_{ij}
+\gamma_i\mathcal H(\mathcal M_i)\bigr)}
\]

is **non‑identifiable** whenever a latent variable \(U_i\) (e.g., substrate influence or neural‑model over‑fitting) simultaneously affects the alignment outcome and the entropy term \(\mathcal H(\mathcal M_i)\) in an additive way, and the observed covariates \(\kappa_{ij}\) (geographic kernel) and \(\phi_{ij}\) (shared‑feature overlap) are linearly independent across the neighbour set \(\mathcal N(i)\). Under these conditions an infinite family of parameter triples \((\alpha,\beta,\gamma)\) yields the same observable joint distribution, because the effect of \(U_i\) can be absorbed into a re‑parameterisation of the linear coefficients.

A **causal identification strategy** that isolates the genuine areal effect uses Pearl’s do‑calculus. By conditioning on the observed entropy (or, equivalently, intervening on the neural model so that \(\mathcal H\) is held constant across languages), the back‑door path \(G_{ij}\!\leftarrow\!U_i\!\rightarrow\!\mathcal H\!\rightarrow\!A_i\) is blocked. The do‑expression for the pure areal effect is therefore identifiable as  

\[
\boxed{
P\!\bigl(A_i\mid do(G_{ij}=g),do(F_{ij}=f)\bigr)
=\sum_{e} P\!\bigl(A_i\mid G_{ij}=g,F_{ij}=f,E_i=e\bigr)\,P(E_i=e)
}
\]

where \(E_i=\mathcal H(\mathcal M_i)\). Practically, one estimates \(E_i\) on held‑out data, stratifies or regresses \(A_i\) on \((G_{ij},F_{ij},E_i)\), and then averages over the marginal distribution of \(E_i\). A stronger intervention—re‑training all language models under identical architecture and hyper‑parameters (\(\mathcal M^\star\))—removes the entropy‑driven confounding altogether:

\[
P\!\bigl(A_i\mid do(G_{ij}=g),do(F_{ij}=f),do(\mathcal M=\mathcal M^\star)\bigr)
=\sum_{e} P\!\bigl(A_i\mid G_{ij}=g,F_{ij}=f,E_i=e,\mathcal M^\star\bigr)\,P(E_i=e\mid\mathcal M^\star).
\]

Thus, by (i) recognizing the latent confounder, (ii) verifying the linear‑independence condition, and (iii) applying the back‑door adjustment (or a controlled model‑intervention), one can disentangle true areal diffusion from algorithmic artifacts in the proposed stochastic framework.

**Conclusion**  
The loss of PDR1 removes a steric block on the E3 subunit, which raises the intrinsic turnover (higher k_cat) of the plastidial PDHc when NAD⁺ is limiting—hence the increased *in vitro* activity. In vivo, photorespiratory illumination drives the stromal NADH/NAD⁺ ratio (ρ) high; the now‑unrestricted E3 site becomes a strong target for NADH‑mediated product inhibition, and the excess NADH also fuels malate accumulation (via MDH) and activates the glyoxylate shunt. These three redox‑dependent feedbacks together suppress the net PDHc flux by ~60 % despite the kinetic gain.

---

### Mechanistic model

The net flux of PDHc in the *pdr1* knockout is described by a Michaelis–Menten core multiplied by three regulatory factors:

\[
v_{\text{PDH}}^{\Delta pdr1}(t)=
\frac{k_{\text{cat}}^{\Delta pdr1}\,[E_{\text{PDH}}](t)\,[\text{Pyr}]}
      {K_{M}^{\Delta pdr1}+[\text{Pyr}]}
\;f_{\text{NADH}}(\rho)\;
f_{\text{Mal}}(\rho)\;
f_{\text{Glyox}}(\rho)
\]

where  

* \(f_{\text{NADH}}(\rho)=\displaystyle\frac{1}{1+\rho/K_{i}^{\text{NADH}}}\) (NADH inhibition of E3)  
* \(f_{\text{Mal}}(\rho)=\displaystyle\frac{1}{1+\alpha_{\text{Mal}}\;\frac{\rho}{K_{M}^{\text{MDH}}+\rho}}\) (malate feedback via MDH)  
* \(f_{\text{Glyox}}(\rho)=\displaystyle\frac{1}{1+\frac{V_{\max}^{\text{Glyox}}}{K_{G}}\;\frac{\rho}{K_{G}+\rho}}\) (acetyl‑CoA diversion to the glyoxylate shunt)  

\([E_{\text{PDH}}](t)=E^{\text{max}}\;D_{\text{PDH‑E1α}}(t)\;D_{\text{DLD}}(t)\) reflects the diurnal expression of the catalytic subunits.

---

### Effective catalytic efficiency

Defining the effective catalytic efficiency as the flux per unit enzyme and substrate, the dimensionless quantity \(\epsilon_{\text{eff}}(t)\) becomes

\[
\boxed{
\epsilon_{\text{eff}}(t)=
\frac{1}{1+\dfrac{[\text{Pyr}]}{K_{M}^{\Delta pdr1}}}\;
\underbrace{\frac{1}{1+\rho/K_{i}^{\text{NADH}}}}_{f_{\text{NADH}}}\;
\underbrace{\frac{1}{1+\alpha_{\text{Mal}}\;\dfrac{\rho}{K_{M}^{\text{MDH}}+\rho}}}_{f_{\text{Mal}}}\;
\underbrace{\frac{1}{1+\dfrac{V_{\max}^{\text{Glyox}}}{K_{G}}\;\dfrac{\rho}{K_{G}+\rho}}}_{f_{\text{Glyox}}}
}
\]

- The first term accounts for substrate saturation.  
- The three subsequent terms encode, respectively, (i) allosteric inhibition by NADH, (ii) feedback inhibition by malate produced by MDH, and (iii) loss of acetyl‑CoA to the NADH‑driven glyoxylate shunt.  

When \(\rho\) is low (oxidative, *in vitro* conditions) the three regulatory factors approach 1, so \(\epsilon_{\text{eff}}\) is close to the classic Michaelis–Menten efficiency and the kinetic advantage of the mutant is observed. Under photorespiratory, highly reduced conditions (\(\rho\approx0.8\)), the product of the three factors drops dramatically, overwhelming the kinetic gain and yielding the ~60 % reduction in in‑vivo flux. This integrated model reconciles the apparent paradox.

